{"key":"post-9544148","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9544148</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Please stop spreading this outdated misinformation!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Experience based on direct observation is not outdated info fred.&amp;nbsp; Somewhere around here I have a picture of one of those hepa filters after I removed the filter to change it.&amp;nbsp; There was nearly as much dust on the gasket and housing as in the filter itself.&amp;nbsp; In addition, the output grill was covered with dust that couldn't have gotten there without going through/around the filter.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As said, I bought several models of these from lowes and home depot, and the most expensive unit was a kenmore model from sears.&amp;nbsp; All performed the same.&amp;nbsp; Perhaps you guys aren't doing agar work, but in my experience, a still air box works better than positive pressure, and a true laminar flow hood beats them all.&amp;nbsp; That's speaking from direct experience, so mind your tone please.&amp;nbsp; It isn't a fight-it's passing on knowledge.&amp;nbsp; If your experience is different, feel free to share your views.&amp;nbsp; We've had this discussion before over the years.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Depending on ambient contaminant spore load, there's a huge difference between a filter that traps 99.9% of contaminants under .3 microns, one that traps 99.99% of contaminants under .3 microns, and one that traps 99.995% of contaminants under .3 microns.&amp;nbsp;  Those in low contaminant load areas can probably get by with a cheaper filter.&amp;nbsp; Those of us near rain forest full of trich, or who go hiking/camping all the time in trichoderma infested forests bring a much higher spore load back into our work areas.&amp;nbsp; In addition, one trich outbreak in a grow area releases a few billion spores.&amp;nbsp; If your filter stops 99.9% of a few billion spores, it still lets through many thousands that can ruin your day.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9544264</next>\n<prev>9544126</prev>\n<first>9540551</first>\n<last>9548512</last>\n<when>1231104875</when>\n<utime>01/04/09 11:34 PM</utime>\n</post>"}